issue.title: No 60 Hz line filter on the OpenBCI 32 Bit board.
issue.body:
The OpenBCI 32 bit board does not have a 60Hz line filter. This code is misleading because the filter will not have an effect.

``` python
  def enable_filters(self):
    """
    Adds a filter at 60hz to cancel out ambient electrical noise.
    """
    self.ser.write('f')
    self.filtering_data = True

  def disable_filters(self):
    self.ser.write('g')
    self.filtering_data = False
```

[Link to lines of code for issue](https://github.com/marionleborgne/cloudbrain/blob/master/cloudbrain/connectors/openbci/OpenBCIBoard.py#L103-L112)

issue.title: Enable Cross Origin Requests in Python API
issue.body:
We can enable cross-origin requests in the initial phase in the API adding the CORS headers in the response:

```
Access-Control-Allow-Methods:POST,GET,OPTIONS,DELETE,PUT
Access-Control-Allow-Origin:*
```

In this way, we can write the fronted and javascript API in a clean way from the beginning (without using JSONP or other tricks). Afterwords, we can deal with AAA aspects and determine how the API will be accessed  (e.g., OAuth, etc.)

issue.title: Pipe publisher and subscriber
issue.body:
Add simple pipe publisher and subscriber, an easy way to get data out of cloudbrain.

With this pull request, saving data to a csv is as easy as:
`python2 cloudbrain/publishers/pipe_publisher.py --mock -n muse -i octopicorn | python2 cloudbrain/subscribers/file_writer_subscriber.py -i octopicorn -n muse -m eeg -s pipe`

You can also have a pipe publisher and subscriber:

```
python2 cloudbrain/publishers/pipe_publisher.py --mock -n muse -i octopicorn  -o /tmp/test
python2 cloudbrain/subscribers/file_writer_subscriber.py -i octopicorn -n muse -m eeg -s pipe --pipe /tmp/test
```
